Title : India–Yemen relations
Text : {{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of India and the Republic of Yemen}}
{{More citations needed|date=April 2014}}
{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Indian–Yemenite|India|Yemen|map=India Yemen Locator (cropped).png}}

'''India–Yemen relations''' refer to the [[bilateralism|current and historical relationship]] of the [[India]] and [[Yemen]]. Diplomatic relations between these countries were established in November 1967 when India recognized Yemen's independence from the [[United Kingdom]]. Relations continue to be in good shape notwithstanding [[Indo-Saudi Arabian relations|India's close partnership with Saudi Arabia]] or [[Pakistan–Yemen relations|Yemen's close ties with Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=|url=http://www.yementimes.com/article.shtml?i=1122&p=local&a=7|accessdate=|quote=}}</ref>

India has an embassy in [[Sana'a]], while Yemen has an embassy in [[New Delhi]].

==History==
{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2014}}
In 1839, [[Aden]] became part of the [[British Empire]] and was administered by the [[Bombay Presidency]]. A garrison of 2000 Indian soldiers was established in Aden and the [[Indian Rupee]] was made the official currency.  In 1855, a fortnightly steamer service with Bombay was initiated by Peninsular and Orient Line. Engineer of India, was sent by the British to Aden in 1906 to lay out an effective underground drainage system and to prepare a scheme for providing drinking water.

===Yemenite Civil War===

{{further|1994 civil war in Yemen}}

During the outbreak of the Civil War India took a neutral stand. Indian doctors and nurses were perhaps the only expatriates who stayed behind and rendered humanitarian services to the people of Yemen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yemen: The Covert Apparatus of the American Empire|url=http://andrewgavinmarshall.com/2011/07/15/yemen-the-covert-apparatus-of-the-american-empire/|accessdate=October 5, 2010|quote=}}. October 5, 2010.</ref> In July 1994, following the successful conclusion of the Civil War, the Government of Yemen sought the help of the Government of India in admitting over 150 war-wounded persons for medical treatment in the hospitals in Bombay, which was readily agreed to by the Indian side.

{{further|Yemeni Crisis (2011–present)}}
Following the [[2015 military intervention in Yemen]] led by [[Saudi Arabia]] to quell the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015–present)|Houthi Rebellion]], India undertook [[Operation Raahat]]. In the operation, [[Indian Armed Forces]] evacuated  more than 4640 Indian citizens along with 960 foreign nationals of 41 countries <ref name="http://www.hindustantimes.com/ 2015">{{cite web | title=4,000 Indians rescued so far, Yemen air evacuation op to end on Wed | website=hindustantimes.com | date=2015-04-07 | url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/4-000-indians-rescued-so-far-yemen-air-evacuation-op-to-end-on-wed/article1-1334906.aspx | accessdate=2015-04-07}}</ref>

